&a\equiv 2\pmod 3,\\
&a\equiv 4\pmod 5,\\
&a\equiv 6\pmod 7,\\
&a\equiv 8\pmod 9.
\end{align*}

solution:
 Superintendent
This problem is an example of Chinese Remainder Theorem. We have a system of congruences:

\begin{align*}
a \equiv 2 \pmod{3},\\
a \equiv 4 \pmod{5},\\
a \equiv 6 \pmod{7},\\
a \equiv 8 \pmod{9}.
\end{align*}

We can solve this by finding a number that satisfies all the congruences. Let's start by finding a common solution for the first two congruences:

\begin{align*}
a &\equiv 2 \pmod{3},\\
a &\equiv 4 \pmod{5}.
\end{align*}

We can express $a$ as $3k + 2$ for some integer $k$. Then we can substitute this into the second congruence:

\begin{align*}
3k + 2 &\equiv 4 \pmod{5},\\
3k &\equiv 2 \pmod{5}.
\end{align*}

To solve for $k$, we can multiply both sides by the modular inverse of $3$ modulo $5$, which is $2$ (since $3 \times 2 \equiv 1 \pmod{5}$):

\begin{align*}
k &\equiv 4 \times 2 \pmod{5},\\
k &\equiv 8 \pmod{5},\\
k &\equiv 3 \pmod{5}.
\end{align*}

