So we can express $n$ as $7p + 1$ for some integer $p$. Substituting this back into our expression for $a$, we get:

\begin{align*}
a &= 15(7p + 1) + 11,\\
a &= 105p + 26.
\end{align*}

Finally, we apply the last congruence:

\begin{align*}
a &\equiv 26 \pmod{9},\\
a &\equiv 8 \pmod{9}.
\end{align*}

We can express $a$ as $9q + 8$ for some integer $q$. Then we can substitute this into the second congruence:

\begin{align*}
9q + 8 &\equiv 8 \pmod{9},\\
9q &\equiv 0 \pmod{9},\\
q &\equiv 0 \pmod{9}.
\end{align*}

So we can express $q$ as $9r$ for some integer $r$. Substituting this back into our expression for $a$, we get:

\begin{align*}
a &= 9(9r) + 8,\\
a &= 82.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the smallest positive integer $a$ that satisfies all the given congruences is $82$.

